---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';

const plumbing = [
  {
    num: '01',
    body: 'Fetch the second repo, and get it onto the right branch.',
  },
  {
    num: '02',
    body: 'Set up worktrees so the agents can work in each repo independently without stepping on each other.',
  },
  {
    num: '03',
    body: 'Route context by hand: CLAUDE.md files, custom scripts, copied-in markdown, so each agent knows what the other is doing.',
  },
  {
    num: '04',
    body: 'Once the work is done, figure out how to push the coordinated PRs so they land together instead of breaking each other.',
  },
];
---

<section id="barrier" class="px-6 py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
      The catch
    </p>
    <h2
      class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
    >
      The same barrier, again
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
      At that new altitude you hit the exact stitching problem from before, one
      level up. You are now looking at the backend repo and the frontend repo at
      once, but the harness is local to each. To make one agent work across both,
      you become the plumbing. Concretely, today, with just a harness:
    </p>

    <ol
      class="mt-8 divide-y divide-neutral-800 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-neutral-800"
    >
      {
        plumbing.map((step) => (
          <li class="bg-neutral-950 p-6">
            <div class="flex items-baseline gap-4">
              <span class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">{step.num}</span>
              <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
                {step.body}
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>

    <div class="mt-10 space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
      <p>
        And that is only the first problem. The second one is quieter and worse.
        You spent a session with an agent working through a tricky piece of the
        system, and a lot of reasoning went into it: why this approach, what you
        ruled out, where the sharp edges are. <mark>Where does that go?</mark>
        The session log is a file on your machine. In a month, when a bug report
        lands on exactly that feature, you want to pull that reasoning back, and
        there is nowhere it lives that you or anyone else can reach.
      </p>
      <p class="font-medium text-neutral-100">
        Everyone hits these two problems right now, cross-repo plumbing and
        session knowledge with nowhere to live. That is the harness gap.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-5xl">
    <VizPlaceholder
      label="two repos side by side with hand-drawn worktrees, scripts, and CLAUDE.md wires between them, and a session log falling off the edge of one laptop"
    />
  </div>
</section>
